<h2 style="font-family:verdana; color:#333">Place Value House</h2>

<div style="line-height:2">
<p style="font-family:verdana; color:#333">Numbers are made up of digits. The digit can be any number from 0 to 9. Place value is the position of each digit in a number. Use this Place Value House with counting sticks to demonstrate the value of each digit in a number.</p>

<p style="font-family:verdana; color:#333">The Place Value House contains three columns that represent Hundreds, Tens and Ones. Form a number by dragging the number block into the corresponding place value. For example, the number 25 is made up of digit 2 and 5. The digit 2 is in the tens place while the digit 5 in the ones place.</p>

<p style="font-family:verdana; color:#333">Then drag the counting sticks to show the value of the digit. Each individual stick represents one and each bundle of sticks represents ten. 25 have 2 tens and 5 ones. 2 tens equal to 20 so, drag two bundles of sticks in the tens column; 5 ones equals to 5 so, drag five individual sticks in the ones column.</p>

<p style="font-family:verdana; color:#333">To discard a block or stick, drag and drop it out of the Place Value House. This Place Value House able to demonstrate the value of numbers up to 99.</p>
</div>